    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Pharmacies and Medications</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Pharmacies (аптека) are widely available throughout Bulgaria. Many medications that require prescriptions in Western countries are available over-the-counter in Bulgaria. Prices are significantly lower than Western Europe or North America. Major chains include Remedium and Sopharmacy.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-green-800">
        <strong>Prescription medications:</strong> If you need regular medications, bring your prescription and a doctor's letter. Bulgarian pharmacists can often provide equivalents, but some specialized medications may need to be sourced from your home country initially.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the minimum income for Bulgaria's digital nomad visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The income requirement is 50 times Bulgaria's minimum wage, which translates to approximately €31,000/year or €2,300-2,600/month. You must demonstrate stable, recurring income from clients or employers outside Bulgaria—bank statements and contracts from the past 6-12 months typically satisfy this requirement.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I travel freely in Europe with Bulgaria's DNV?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Bulgaria joined the Schengen Zone in 2025, so your residence permit allows visa-free travel throughout the Schengen Area. You can visit Portugal, Spain, Germany, France, Italy, and other Schengen countries without additional visas—perfect for weekend trips or client meetings.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What tax rate will I pay as a digital nomad in Bulgaria?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          If you become a tax resident (183+ days in Bulgaria), you pay 10% flat income tax—the lowest in the EU. Social security contributions may apply depending on your situation. Consult a Bulgarian tax advisor to optimize your setup, especially if you're coming from a higher-tax country.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long can I stay on Bulgaria's digital nomad visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The residence permit is issued for 1 year and can be renewed once, allowing up to 2 years total on the DNV. After that, you would need to explore other visa options (such as a standard work permit or business visa) or transition to a different country.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Bulgarian for daily life?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          In Sofia and other major cities, English is widely spoken among young people and in business settings. However, Bulgarian helps with bureaucracy, healthcare, and daily interactions. The Cyrillic alphabet can be challenging initially—learning basic phrases and the alphabet makes life easier.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What currency does Bulgaria use?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Bulgaria adopted the Euro in 2025, replacing the Bulgarian Lev. This simplifies finances if you earn in Euros or work with Eurozone clients. Prices remain low by EU standards—Sofia offers Western European amenities at Eastern European prices.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

